  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Crow-Armstrong Blasts Giants for Cubs Walk-Off in Ten Innings",
    "subheadline": "Pete Crow-Armstrong's Two-Homer Effort Powers Cubs to 10th-Inning Victory",
    "lead_angle": "Pete Crow-Armstrong silenced the San Francisco Giants at Wrigley Field, driving a two-run shot deep to right in the bottom of the tenth inning for a 3-2 walk-off victory. The decisive shot off losing pitcher Sam Hentges sent the Chicago Cubs faithful into a frenzy, capping a dramatic afternoon where both teams clawed for every inch.\n\nThe tenth frame opened with the Giants breaking the 1-1 deadlock. Jung Hoo Lee singled to lead off, then advanced on a Michael Busch error. Rafael Devers then plated Lee with a sharp grounder, putting the visiting nine ahead 2-1. But the Cubs refused to yield. Michael Busch atoned for his error with a leadoff walk in the home half. Two batters later, Crow-Armstrong stepped in, sending Hentges' offering soaring over the ivy.\n\nCrow-Armstrong's bat was the deciding factor for Chicago, finishing 4-for-5 with both of the Cubs' home runs and all two of their runs batted in. Ryan Rolison earned the victory in relief, navigating the top of the tenth before Crow-Armstrong's heroics. This tight extra-inning win at home provides a critical boost for the Chicago Cubs in a close National League Central race, holding off a road victory for the San Francisco Giants who are also battling for position.",
    "reason": "Extra-inning walk-off — the purest combination of tension and resolution the sport offers."
  },
